2.3 Properties of Probability Measures
The probability of the null event is 0.

\mathbb{P}r(\emptyset) = 0
\tag{2.9}
Probabilities of all possible events (the space of all possible outcomes) must sum to one.

\mathbb{P}r(\Omega) = 1
\tag{2.10}

A\cap B = \emptyset \implies \mathbb{P}r(A \cup B) = \mathbb{P}r(A)+\mathbb{P}r(B)
\tag{2.11}


\mathbb{P}r(A^c) =1-\mathbb{P}r(A) \qquad \forall A\in\Omega
\tag{2.12}

if A is an event in \Omega then A^C is in Omega and since they are mutually exclusive by Equation¬†2.10
If S is the certain event in class C \Omega then
For every event X in class \Omega

1 \ge \mathbb{P}r(X) \ge 0 \qquad \forall X \in \Omega \qquad \text{(P1)} \qquad
\tag{2.13}
Probabilities add to one:

\sum_{i\in \Omega} \mathbb{P}r(X=i)=1 \qquad \text{(P2)}\qquad
\tag{2.14}
The complement of an event A is A^c

\mathbb{P}r(S) = 1
\tag{2.15}
If events A_\lambda are mutually exclusive (only one event may happen):

\mathbb{P}r(A_1 \cup A_2) = \mathbb{P}r(A_1) + \mathbb{P}r(A_2) - \mathbb{P}r(A_1\cap A_1)
\tag{2.16}

\mathbb{P}r(\bigcup_{\lambda\in \Omega} A_\lambda)=\sum_{\lambda \in \Omega} \mathbb{P}r(A_\lambda)
\tag{2.17}
if {B_i} is a finite or countably infinite partition of a sample space \Omega then

\mathbb{P}r(A) = {\sum_{i=1}^{N} \mathbb{P}r(A \cap B_i)}= {\sum_{i=1}^{N} \mathbb{P}r(A|B_i)\mathbb{P}r(B_i)}
\tag{2.18}

2.3.1 Odds

C-3PO: Sir, the possibility of successfully navigating an asteroid field is approximately 3,720 to 1!  Han Solo: Never tell me the odds! ‚Äî Star Wars Episode V: The Empire Strikes Back

Another way to think about probabilities is using odds Equation¬†2.19. Odds are more intuitive when we are thinking about the risk of an event happening or not happening. and when we consider the risk associated with uncertainty odds are a handy way of considering the risks.

Definition 2.10 (Odds Definitions) the odds of an event A are:

\mathcal{O}(A)  = \frac{\mathbb{P}r(A)}{\mathbb{P}r(A^c)} = \frac{ \mathbb{P}r(A)}{1-\mathbb{P}r(A)}
\tag{2.19}

It is also possible to convert odds to probabilities Equation¬†2.20

Theorem 2.1 (Probability from odds) 
\mathbb{P}r(A) = \frac{ \mathcal{O}(A)} {1+ \mathcal{O}(A)}
\tag{2.20}


Proof. 
\begin{aligned}
& & \mathcal{O}(A)  &= \frac{\mathbb{P}r(A)}{1-\mathbb{P}r(A)} && \text{(odds definition)} \\
   &\implies & \mathbb{P}r(A) &= \mathcal{O}(A) (1-\mathbb{P}r(A))  && (\times \text{ denominator}) \\
   &\implies &  \mathbb{P}r(A) &= \mathcal{O}(A) - \mathcal{O}(A) \mathbb{P}r(A) && \text{(expand)} \\
   &\implies &  \mathbb{P}r(A)(1+ \mathcal{O}(A)) &= \mathcal{O}(A) && \text{(collect)}   \\
   &\implies & \mathbb{P}r(A) &= \frac{ \mathcal{O}(A)} {1+ \mathcal{O}(A)} && \blacksquare  
\end{aligned}


If we are at the races and thinking about each horse a horse what we may care about is if it will win or lose. In such a case the odds can summarize the ratio of past successes and failures to win. Odds seem to be in line with a frequentist view summarizing ratios of success to failure. In reality, the other horses have odds as well and we may want to consider the probability of winning given the other horses in the race, and perhaps other parameters, like the track type, length of the race, jockey, and perhaps some hot tips. So let us not get ahead of ourselves






TipData Scientist - insights.



Many of these formulas are rather tedious. But, once you start to work on a data science project you will often discover that there are some problems with the data and because of that you cannot use your favorite algorithm. Or worse when you do the results are not very useful. It is at this point that the ability to think back to first principles will be very fruitful. The more of this material you can recall, the more the dots will connect, and your ability will translate into models of increasing sophistication. Luckily, the rules of probability are logical. So it is fairly easy to remember or even derive if you take some time to understand them.
I realize that figuring out which results are more useful is easier in hindsight. And one of the reasons I am taking these courses is to annotate in my note the results I think to be most useful.




2.3.2 Expectation
The expectation of a random variable (RV) X is the weighted average of the outcomes it can take weighted by their probabilities.

Definition 2.11 (Expectation for a discrete RV) 
\mathbb{E}(x) = \sum^N_{i=1} x_i \times \mathbb{P}r(X=x_i)
\tag{2.21}


Definition 2.12 (Expectation for a continuous RV) 
\mathbb{E}(x) = \int_{\Omega} x \mathbb{P}r(X=x) dx
\tag{2.22}

2.8 Variance
Variance is the dispersion of a distribution about the mean.

Definition 2.16 For a discrete random variable, the Variance is defined using (Equation¬†2.29)

\mathbb{V}ar(X)=\sum^N_{i=1} (x_i-\mu)^2 \mathbb{P}r(X=x_i)
\tag{2.29}


Definition 2.17 For a continuous random variable, the Variance is defined using (Equation¬†2.30)

\mathbb{V}ar[X]=\int_{- \infty}^{\infty} (x-\mu)^2 f(x)dx
\tag{2.30}


2.8.1 Properties of Variance

\mathbb{V}ar[c] = 0
\tag{2.31}
if X and Y are independent then

\mathbb{V}ar[aX+by] = a^2\mathbb{V}ar[X] +b^2\mathbb{V}ar[Y]
\tag{2.32}
otherwise

\mathbb{V}ar[aX+by] = a^2\mathbb{V}ar[X] +b^2\mathbb{V}ar[Y] + 2ab\mathbb{C}ov(X,Y)
\tag{2.33}
where \mathbb{C}ov(X,Y) is the covariance of X and Y.
Here is one of the most useful identities (Equation¬†2.34) for wrangling with variance using the expectation of X and X^2.

\begin{aligned}
    \mathbb{V}ar[X] &= \mathbb{E}[(X- \mathbb{E}[X])^2]
    \\&= \mathbb{E}[X^2] ‚àí (\mathbb{E}[X])^2
\end{aligned}
\tag{2.34}

2.9 Covariance
Covariance is a measure of the joint variability of two random variables. It indicates the direction of the linear relationship between the variables.
If X and Y are two random variables, the covariance of X and Y is defined as:

\begin{aligned}
\mathrm{Cov}(X,Y) &= \mathbb{E}[(X-\mathbb{E}[X])(Y-\mathbb{E}[Y])]
\\ &= \mathbb{E}[XY]-\mathbb{E}[X]\mathbb{E}[Y]
\end{aligned}
\tag{2.35}

4.2 Conditional Probability







Figure¬†4.1: conditional probability



\mathbb{P}r(A \mid B)=\frac{\mathbb{P}r(A \cap B)}{\mathbb{P}r(B)}
\tag{4.1}
independence

\mathbb{P}r(A \mid B) = \mathbb{P}r(A) \implies \mathbb{P}r(A \cap B) = \mathbb{P}r(A)\mathbb{P}r(B)
\tag{4.2}

4.2.1 Conditional Probability Example - Female CS Student
Suppose there are 30 students, 9 of whom are female. Of the 30 students, 12 are computer science majors. 4 of those 12 computer science majors are female. We want to estimate what is the probability of a student being female given that she is a computer science major We start by writing the above in the language of probability by converting frequencies to probabilities. We start with the marginal. First, the probability of a student being female from the data given above.

\mathbb{P}r(\text{Female}) = \frac{9}{30} = \frac{3}{10}

Next, we estimate the probability of a student being a computer science major again just using the data given above.

\mathbb{P}r(CS) = \frac{12}{30} = \frac{2}{5}

Next, we can estimate the joint probability, i.e.¬†the probability of being female and being a CS major. Again we have been given the numbers in the data above.

\mathbb{P}r(F\cap CS) = \frac{4}{30} = \frac{2}{15}

Finally, we can use the definition of conditional probability and substitute the above

\mathbb{P}r(F \mid CS) = \frac{\mathbb{P}r(F \cap CS)}{\mathbb{P}r(CS)} = \frac{2/15}{2/5} = \frac{1}{3}
\tag{4.3}

An intuitive way to think about a conditional probability is that we‚Äôre looking at a sub-segment of the original population, and asking a probability question within that segment

\mathbb{P}r(F \mid CS^c) = \frac{\mathbb{P}r(F\cap CS^c)}{ \mathbb{P}r (CS^c)} = \frac{5/30}{18/30} = \frac{5}{18}
\tag{4.4}
The concept of independence is when one event does not depend on another.

A \perp \!\!\! \perp B \iff \mathbb{P}r(A \mid B) = \mathbb{P}r(A)

It doesn‚Äôt matter that B occurred.
If two events are independent then the following is true:

A \perp \!\!\! \perp B \iff \mathbb{P}r(A\cap B) = \mathbb{P}r(A)\mathbb{P}r(B)
\tag{4.5}
This can be derived from the conditional probability equation.

4.2.2 Inverting Conditional Probabilities
If we don‚Äôt know \mathbb{P}r(A \mid B) but we do know the inverse probability \mathbb{P}r(B \mid A) is. We can then rewrite \mathbb{P}r(A \mid B) in terms of \mathbb{P}r(B \mid A)

\mathbb{P}r(A \mid B) = \frac{\mathbb{P}r(B \mid A)\mathbb{P}r(A)}{\mathbb{P}r(B \mid A)\mathbb{P}r(A) + \mathbb{P}r(B \mid A^c)\mathbb{P}r(A^c)}
\tag{4.6}


4.2.3 Conditional Probability Example - ELISA HIV test







Video¬†4.1


Let‚Äôs look at an example of an early test for HIV antibodies known as the ELISA test. - The test has a true positive rate of 0.977. - It has a true negative rate of 0.926. - The incidence of HIV in North America is .0026.
Now we want to know the probability of an individual having the disease given that they tested positive \mathbb{P}r(HIV | +).
This is the inverse probability of the true positive, so we will need to use Bayes‚Äô theorem.
We start by encoding the above using mathematical notation, so we know what to substitute into Bayes‚Äô theorem.
The true positive rate is:

\mathbb{P}r(+ \mid HIV) = 0.977

The true negative rate is:

\mathbb{P}r(- \mid NO\_HIV) = 0.926

The probability of someone in North America having this disease was

\mathbb{P}r(HIV) = .0026

what we want is: \mathbb{P}r(HIV \mid +)

\begin{aligned}
\mathbb{P}r(HIV \mid +) &= \frac{\mathbb{P}r(+ \mid HIV)\mathbb{P}r(HIV)}{\mathbb{P}r(+ \mid HIV)\mathbb{P}r(HIV) + \mathbb{P}r(+ \mid NO\_HIV){\mathbb{P}r(NO\_HIV)}}  \\
&= \frac{(.977)(.0026)}{(.977)(.0026) + (1-.977)(1-.0026)}  \\
&=  0.033
\end{aligned}
\tag{4.7}
This is a bit of a surprise - although the test has 90% + true and false accuracy - taking it once is only valid 3% of the time. How is this possible?
What happens in Bayes law is that we are updating probabilities. And since we started with such a low probability of .0026, Bayesian updating only brings it up to 0.03.

\begin{aligned}
\mathbb{P}r(A \mid B) = \frac{\mathbb{P}r(B \mid A_1){(A_1)}}{\sum_{i=1}^{n}{\mathbb{P}r(B \mid A_i)}\mathbb{P}r(A_i)} \end{aligned}
\tag{4.8}

Note: (McElreath (2015)) discusses how this can be presented less surprisingly.

