Figure¬†32.1: Components of a Bayesian Model




 The likelihood is the probabilistic model for the data. It describes how, given the unknown parameters, the data might be generated. We‚Äôre going to call unknown parameter theta right here. Also, in this expression, you might recognize this from the previous class, as describing a probability distribution.\mathbb{P}r(y\mid \theta)\ \text{(likelihood)}
 The prior, the next step, is the probability distribution that characterizes our uncertainty with the parameter theta. We‚Äôre going to write it as \mathbb{P}r(\theta). It‚Äôs not the same distribution as this one. We‚Äôre just using this notation p to represent the probability distribution of theta. By specifying a likelihood and a prior.\mathbb{P}r(\theta)\ \text{(prior)}
 We now have a joint probability model for both the knowns, the data, and the unknowns, the parameters. We can see this by using the chain rule of probability. If we wanted the joint distribution of both the data and the parameters theta. Using the chain rule of probability, we could start with the distribution of \theta. And multiply that by the probability or the distribution of y given theta. That gives us an expression for the joint distribution. However if we‚Äôre going to make inferences about data and we already know the values of y, we don‚Äôt need the joint distribution, what we need is the posterior distribution.\mathbb{P}r(y,\theta) = \mathbb{P}r(\theta)\mathbb{P}r(y\mid\theta) \ \text{(joint probability)}
 The posterior distribution is the distribution of \mathbb{P}r(\theta \mid y), i.e.¬†\theta given y. We can obtain this expression using the laws of conditional probability and specifically using Bayes‚Äô theorem.\mathbb{P}r(\theta \mid y)\ \text{(posterior)}


 We start with the joint distribution like we have on top, and we integrate out or marginalize over the values of theta (2)How do we get the marginal distribution of y?








NoteAnatomy of a posterior probability




  \begin{aligned}
  &\mathbb{P}r(y\mid \theta) && (likelihood) \\
&  \mathbb{P}r(\theta) && (prior) \\
   \mathbb{P}r(y,\theta) &= \mathbb{P}r(\theta)\mathbb{P}r(y|\theta) &&(joint\ distribution) \\
   \mathbb{P}r(\theta \mid y) &= \frac{\mathbb{P}r(\theta,y)}{\mathbb{P}r(y)} && (conditional\ probability) \\
&= \frac{\mathbb{P}r(\theta,y)}{\int \mathbb{P}r(\theta,y)} \\
&= \frac{\mathbb{P}r(y \mid \theta)\ \mathbb{P}r(\theta)}{\int \mathbb{P}r(y \mid \theta)\ \mathbb{P}r(\theta)\ d\theta} \\
\end{aligned}
\tag{32.1}



Whereas non-Bayesian approaches consider a probability model for the data only, the hallmark characteristic of Bayesian models is that they specify a joint probability distribution for both data and parameters. How does the Bayesian paradigm leverage this additional assumption?



This allows us to make probabilistic assessments about how likely our particular data outcome is under any parameter setting.
This allows us to select the most accurate prior distribution.
This allows us to make probabilistic assessments about hypothetical data outcomes given particular parameter values.
This allows us to use the laws of conditional probability to describe our updated information about parameters given the data.

