Regression models


94.4.1 Simple dynamic regression

\begin{aligned}
y_t &= \beta_{t,0} + \beta_{t,1}x_t + ŒΩ_t \\
\beta_{t,0} &= \beta_{t‚àí1,0} + \omega_{t,0} \\
\beta_{t,1} &= \beta_{t‚àí1,1} + \omega_{t,1}
\end{aligned}
\tag{94.24}
and so \theta_t = (\beta_t,0, \beta_{t,1})‚Ä≤, F_t = (1, x_t)‚Ä≤ and G = I_2.
This results in a forecast function of the form

f_t(h) = k_{t,0} + k_{t,1}x_{t+h}
\tag{94.25}
where k_{t,0} = \mathbb{E}[\beta_{t,0} \mid \mathcal{D}_t] and k_{t,1} = \mathbb{E}[\beta_{t,1} \mid \mathcal{D}_t].


94.4.2 General dynamic regression

\begin{aligned}
y_t &= \beta_{t,0} + \beta_{t,1}x_{t,1} + \ldots \beta_{t,M} x_{t,M} + ŒΩ_t \\
\beta_{t,m} &= \beta_{t‚àí1,m} + \omega_{t,m,} & m = 0 : M.
\end{aligned}
\tag{94.26}
Then, \theta = (\beta_t,0, \ldots , \beta_{t,M} )‚Ä≤, F_t = (1, x_{t,1}, \ldots , x_{t,M} )‚Ä≤ and G = I_M . The forecast function is given by

f_t(h) = k_{t,0} + k_{t,1}x_{t+h,1} + \ldots + k_{t+h,M}x_{t+h,M}
\tag{94.27}
A particular case is of dynamic regressions is the case of time-varying auto-regressions (TVAR) with

\begin{aligned}
y_t &= \varphi_{t,1}y_{t‚àí1} + \varphi_{t,2}y_{t‚àí2} + \ldots + \varphi_{t,p} y_{t‚àíp} + ŒΩ_t,\\
\varphi_{t,m} &= \varphi_{t‚àí1,m} + \omega_{t,m,} & m = 1 : p
\end{aligned}
\tag{94.28}
There is a paper (Raquel Prado, Huerta, and West 2000) on TVAR models that is a good reference for this model.






