TipHistorical Note on The William Sealy Gosset A.K.A Student



 The student-t distribution is due to Gosset, William Sealy (1876-1937) who was an English statistician, chemist and brewer who served as Head Brewer of Guinness and Head Experimental Brewer of Guinness and was a pioneer of modern statistics. He is known for his pioneering work on small sample experimental designs. Gosset published under the pseudonym ‚ÄúStudent‚Äù and developed most famously Student‚Äôs t-distribution ‚Äì originally called Student‚Äôs ‚Äúz‚Äù ‚Äì and ‚ÄúStudent‚Äôs test of statistical significance‚Äù.
He was told to use a Pseudonym and choose ‚ÄòStudent‚Äô after a predecessor at Guinness published a paper that leaked trade secrets. Gosset was a friend of both Karl Pearson and Ronald Fisher. Fisher suggested a correction to the student-t using the degrees of freedom rather than the sample size. Fisher is also credited with helping to publicize its use.
for a full biography see (Pearson et al. 1990)

