102.2 Natural Logarithms
We will need to manipulate long products of probabilities. Since there often comprise small fractions, their calculation on computers can be problematic due to the underflow of floats. We will therefore prefer to convert these products into sums of logarithms.

Definition 102.1 (The Logarithm) A log is the inverse of a power. We can use (Equation¬†102.1).

y = a^x \implies log_a(y) = x
\tag{102.1}


Definition 102.2 (The Natural log) The natural logarithm function has base e and is written without the subscript

log_e(y) = log(y)
\tag{102.2}


Theorem 102.1 (Logs take positive values) logs only exist for values greater than 0

\forall x(e^x &gt; 0) \implies \exists \log(y) \iff {y &gt; 0}


We can use the properties of exponents from the previous section to obtain some important properties of logarithms:

Definition 102.3 (Log of a product) we can use Equation¬†102.3 to convert a log of a product to a sum of logs.

\log(x¬∑y) = \log(x) + \log(y)
\tag{102.3}


Definition 102.4 (Log of a quotient) we can use Equation¬†102.4 to convert a log of a quotient to a difference of logs.

\log(\frac{x}{y}) = log(x) ‚àí log(y)
\tag{102.4}


Definition 102.5 (Log of a power) we can use Equation¬†102.5 to convert a log of a variable raised to a power into the product.

    \log(x^b) = b \cdot log(x)
\tag{102.5}


Definition 102.6 (Log of one) we can use (Equation¬†102.6) to replace a log of 1 with zero since $x(x^0 = 1) $

    \log(1)=0
\tag{102.6}


102.2.1 Log of exponent
we can use (Equation¬†102.7) to cancel a log of an exponent since the log is the inverse function of the exponent.

exp(log(y)) = log(exp(y)) = y
\tag{102.7}

Example 102.1 (Logarithm) 
    \begin{aligned}
    log \frac{5^2}{10}= 2 log(5) ‚àí log(10) ‚âà 0.916.
    \end{aligned}



Definition 102.7 (Change of base for a log) we can use (Equation¬†102.8) to change the base of a logarithm.

    \log_b(a)=\frac{\log_c(a)}{\log_c(n)}
\tag{102.8}


Definition 102.8 (Derivative of a Log) we can use (Equation¬†102.9) to differentiate a log.

    \frac{d}{dx} \log_(x)=\frac{1}{x}
\tag{102.9}


Because the natural logarithm is a monotonically increasing one-to-one function, finding the x which maximizes any (positive-valued function) f(x) is equivalent to maximizing log(f(x)).
This is useful because we often take derivatives to maximize functions.
If f(x) has product terms, then log(f(x)) will have summation terms, which are usually simpler when taking derivatives.

